{One of the wildest games of the event, with the final result several times in
doubt.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. c3 Ngf6 5. Qe2 a6 6. Ba4 b5 7. Bc2
Bb7 8. d4 g6 9. Nbd2 cxd4 10. cxd4 Bg7 11. O-O O-O 12. Nb3 a5 13. Bg5 h6 14.
Bh4 Nh5 15. Rfe1 b4 16. a4 Re8 17. Qe3 Qb6 18. Nfd2 e5 19. d5 Nf4 20. Nc4 ({
What started out as a Bb5+ Sicilian has turned into a King's Indian type of
position. Here perhaps} 20. Qxb6 $5 Nxb6 21. f3 Rec8 22. Bb1 {followed by Bf2,
gives White some chances for an advantage in the endgame.}) 20... Qc7 21. Nbd2
g5 22. Bg3 f5 23. f3 Rf8 24. Rac1 fxe4 25. fxe4 Rf6 26. Bd1 $1 {Strong
prophylaxis against Black's counterplay on the kingside.} Qd8 ({Could Black
have gone} 26... h5 {anyway? The sample line} 27. Nb3 Qd8 28. Qd2 {
(threatening to take on f4 and h5)} g4 $5 29. Bh4 {looks like an exchange, but
Black goes} Ba6 $1 30. Bxf6 Bxf6 31. Ne3 Bg5 {and it's still very messy!}) 27.
Bg4 Ra6 28. Nb3 {Now White seems to be firmly in control.} Nf8 29. Qd2 N8g6 30.
Bf2 (30. Qd1 $5 {[%csl Gd1,Gg4][%cal Gg4h5,Rh6h5,Gd1g4] would have nipped any
kingside counterplay from Black in the bud.}) 30... h5 31. Bd1 ({Allowing
Black back in the game. Instead} 31. Be6+ $1 {with the idea} Nxe6 32. dxe6 Rxe6
33. Nc5 $1 {would have been very big.}) 31... Nh4 32. Nbxa5 (32. Kh1 $3 Nhxg2
33. Rg1 {is a remarkable idea that was probably worth going for.}) 32... Bc8
33. Nc6 Qf8 34. Bxh4 gxh4 35. Ne3 Bh6 ({Just when Black was about to take
over! Instead} 35... Ra8 $1 {would have stopped White's next move.}) 36. Ne7+
$1 Qxe7 37. Rxc8+ Kh7 38. Qc2 {Once again it is now White who is in control.}
Rf7 39. Nf5 Qg5 40. Bf3 b3 41. Qxb3 Raa7 42. Kh1 h3 43. g3 ({The cold-blooded} 
43. gxh3 Nxh3 44. Rc2 {is likely preferable, preparing a switch to g2. The
game continuation is not yet wrong, but it slowly goes downhill from here.})
43... Ng2 44. Qb8 Bg7 45. Nxg7 Qxg7 46. Bxg2 hxg2+ 47. Kxg2 Qf6 ({I am not
sure wether this is a winning attempt or wether time-trouble was involved. By
now} 47... Rab7 48. Qxd6 Rxb2+ 49. Kg1 Rff2 {is already a straightforward draw!
}) 48. Rc2 (48. Rg8 $1 Rxa4 49. Kh3 {[%csl Gh3] followed by Qd8 is winning.
White's king is remarkably safe on h3! In the game Black is again in the
safety zone.}) 48... Rxa4 (48... Qf3+ $1 49. Kg1 Rxa4 {was the last chance to
escape. For instance} 50. Qxd6 Rxe4 51. Rec1 Qe3+ 52. Kh1 Qf3+ {with a
perpetual.}) 49. Qb3 $1 {covering the entry square f3!} Ra8 50. Qd3 h4 51. gxh4
Qxh4 ({This runs into a very pretty refutation!} 51... Rg7+ 52. Kh1 Qxh4 {is
still giving White big technical difficulties to convert.}) 52. Re3 Ra1 53. Rh3
Rg7+ 54. Qg3 Rg1+ $1 {With the idea of 55.Kxg1 Qxh3! but Alan went} 55. Kf2 $1
{which forced immediate resignation. That's what we call fighting chess:)} 1-0

